data.content:
Here are better MSTest assertions for each case:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Any());              // or CollectionAssert.AreNotEqual(0, users.Count);

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive)); // no built-in predicate version — this one is fine

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3);
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);         // gives "Expected:3 Actual:5" on failure

    // Assert.IsTrue(admin != null);
    Assert.IsNotNull(users.SingleOrDefault(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
}
```

**Key improvements:**

| Instead of | Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsTrue(x.Any())` or `Assert.AreNotEqual(0, x.Count)` | Clearer intent |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, x.Count)` | Shows expected vs actual on failure |
| `Assert.IsTrue(obj != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(obj)` | Explicit null-check message |

MSTest's `CollectionAssert` also offers `Contains`, `AllItemsAreUnique`, `IsSubsetOf`, and `AreEquivalent` (order-insensitive equality) — all worth knowing for list-heavy tests.
